Hey Matt, I'm from Berlin, Germany and started Photography 20 years ago with Dads analogue Nikon. Ten years later I thought about doing some creative things again and bought my first DSLR, a 350 D from canon. I did a lot of portrait and concert stuff that time. A better canon followed and after 3 or 4 years the hobby slept for a while. 2 years ago I thought about doing more photography again and bought a Nikon d2x from a friend and the Nikon 50 mm, cause I thought it would be great to work with a system where analogue cams are still available. So I did more stuff again. Last year I got a Nikon Full Frame and a 14-24 zoom for our trip to America and it was so much fun to take pics of the beautiful landscapes. Can't wait for the next trip, to take more pictures of other beautiful places in the world :)

caption:
Some very short lived colour down at Minnamurra the other week. My last time by the ocean again for a while, so I thought I'd take a quick selfie - you know how it is.

Behind the shot: I set my camera to continuously take photos whilst I ran to position for the selfie (I really need to get a good remote for my Sony). During that time my camera captured 100 or so images over a 1-2 minute timeframe. I then stacked all the images in Photoshop using the statistics script set to 'mean' to average out all the motion of the clouds. In theory, this should look like a photo taken with the equivalent exposure time of 1-2 minutes. It also makes for an amusing time lapse!

Socks. One pair of thin merinos, one pair of thick merinos. If you haven't spent $60 on just those two pairs you haven't spent enough. Wear them both at the same time.

I second wearing liner socks and look into Keen boots, not the most durable but they are crazy comfy

Scapa boots. Get the best you can afford. Don't skimp on your feet when doing multi-day walks. I used to and suffered a few ankle injuries. So got myself some heavy duty full leather Scapa boots for the tough Tasmanian conditions. Tough as nails as well as comfy and supportive. üòâ

caption: I've had this idea/image in my head for about 6 months now, and to finally be able to execute it, exactly how I'd pictured, is really exciting! With the full moon rising just after sunset last week, I packed my camera bag and made my way down to Kiama, my favourite little stretch of coastline in Australia. I plan on doing a series of these "selfies", with my lantern, in various coastal locations around NSW. Where should I go next..?

caption:
Last night, I was challenged by @canonaustralia to test my creativity and take it somewhere I'm pretty unfamiliar with. As you know, I'm quite fond of the odd landscape photo here and there, but it was really refreshing to step outside of my comfort zone and #taketheleap! We were given a bunch of creative briefs to choose from whilst we explored the #statelibrarynsw. The brief I decided to focus on was "#looktotheshadows."
.
And yes, SOME Photoshop was used in the making of this image üòú There's definitely a story to this scene, one that really jumps out at me... How do you interpret this story/photograph?
.

caption: Aaand here is part two of my lantern series! I'm really enjoying capturing this series, as it's quite challenging and a lot fun putting my own unique spin on popular photography locations. Also, it was hard enough holding the lantern and my arm still for 5 seconds, let alone 30!

caption: This particular shot from the lantern series is a four image stack. For the base exposure I used a 3 stop @nisifiltersaustralia ND to get the smoothest water without having to use 'bulb mode'. This resulted in a 30 second exposure. Then I captured the exposure of myself on the rock, without any filters, which was about an 8 second exposure. The third exposure was to light paint the rocks in the foreground, and the final exposure for the stars in the sky. Sure, this could be captured in a single exposure, but the end result would not have been this clean. #nisifiltersau #nisiroadtrip

caption: I really don't know how to explain our first afternoon on safari with @madikwesafarilodge. No amount of words could really do justice to the things we experienced, some for the first time, too! We set out on our sunset safari mission with the intentions of playing it by ear. Soon enough we got the call to say a lion was heard roaring somewhere near one of the water holes. The sun was quickly fading and we decided to head on up the road to find another 'Big 5' member, when all of a sudden, right in the very distance, @jewelszee spotted a pair of eyes staring back at her.. and the rest was history. @southafricaanz #wowsouthafrica

And that's a wrap! Hope you guys enjoyed following along on our #nisiroadtrip this past week. Huge thanks to @nisifiltersaustralia for giving us the opportunity to do what we love with products we love! This was captured with the #nisifiltersau 3 stop soft grad, just to tone down some of the highlights in the sky. Hope you're having a great week!

caption:
#5 of my top 7 photographs from 2015.

One of the best things about moving to @AusOutbackNT is seeing the sky light up like this at night. It really is something that has to be seen to be believed. This is Devils Marbles, about 3 hours North of Alice Springs, and is an astrophotographer's dream come true! I stayed out for about 2 hours on this winters night, exploring in the dark, and came away with a few keepers.

caption:
#4 of my top 7 photographs from 2015.

Ok, so I know this isn't technically an amazing image, but it was a pretty exciting few minutes and it's probably my favourite selfie of the year... if not, all time.

For those of you who have been to Bombo Quarry during big swell, you'll know that it's not uncommon to see waves tower over those columns on the left (yes, the ones I'm standing on). I watched the waves for a good 30 minutes before I decided it was safe enough to climb to that point and capture this image.
